{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. With \HKQJ65 you hold a solid sequence, so the king is the top of touching honors and the safe, attacking choice against notrump.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
In 3\N I count one heart trick (the \HA), three diamonds off \DAQ and \DK, and four clubs once I force out the \CA, with a spade to come for nine. The danger is hearts: I have only the lone \HA stopping that suit, so if I win the first round and West later regains the lead, the run of hearts beats me. The plan is to hold up the \HA, develop clubs while East is exhausted of hearts, and lose the club to the safe hand.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, which looks like the top of a sequence, suggesting West holds the \HQJ and length. I duck, and I duck again on the second heart, only taking my \HA on the third round; that empties East of hearts if the suit is splitting as it appears. From there I knock out the \CA: clubs give me four tricks, joining the heart, three diamonds, and a spade to reach nine. If East wins the \CA, hearts are dead in that hand, so the contract is safe.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The whole hand turned on refusing the \HA until the third round, which severed East from West's long hearts before conceding the club. Counting your single stopper and ducking the right number of times is the heart of hold-up play, and you timed it perfectly.}
