{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H7. From \HKQ8743 the standard notrump lead is fourth-best of your longest, strongest suit, attacking before declarer can set up tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
In 3\N I count three clubs off \CAK and the \CQ, two top spades, one heart, and one diamond, and spades develop to four once I drive out the \SA, which brings me to nine. Hearts are the worry: with just the \HA as a stopper, letting West in early would unleash that long suit. So I hold up the \HA, then establish spades for the extra trick, conceding the lead while West can no longer reach his hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H7, which looks like a fourth-best, hinting at a five- or six-card suit headed by honors. I hold up the \HA, ducking the first heart and winning the second only if forced; ducking once should leave East short. Then I attack spades: forcing out the \SA gives me four spade tricks to add to three clubs, a heart, and a diamond for nine. East is the safe hand for that spade loser, since West's hearts are stranded after the hold-up.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Holding up the \HA bought the time to set up the fourth spade without ever letting West cash his suit. The lesson is the order: duck first, develop second, and lose the lead only once the danger hand is helpless. Cleanly played.}
