{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H9. With \HKQT98 you have a strong interior sequence; the nine is top of that solid run and the right attacking lead against notrump.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
In 3\N I have a long diamond suit worth five tricks off \DKQ opposite \DAJT, plus the \HA and the \SA, which is seven, and the clubs develop a trick to push me toward nine. The hold-up problem is hearts: my only stopper is the \HA, so I must not win cheaply and hand West a way back to a long heart suit. I duck hearts to strip East, run my diamonds, and develop the club for the ninth trick.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H9, top of what looks like a solid sequence, so West rates to hold the \HKQ and length. I hold up the \HA, ducking until the third round so East is unlikely to have a heart left to return. Then five diamond tricks, the \SA, and the heart give me seven, and developing clubs brings the second club to make nine. Conceding a club to East is safe, because by then West's hearts are cut off.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The five-card diamond suit was the engine, but the hold-up in hearts is what kept West off lead long enough to cash it safely. Patience with the lone \HA, then running the long suit, is exactly the technique. Well done.}
