{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. Holding \HKQJ765 you lead the top of your sequence; the king is the standard, safe attacking card against notrump from that holding.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
In 3\N I count one heart trick from the \HA, three or four clubs once the \CJ and \CT are dislodged from \CKQ643 opposite \CA987, and spades develop after I force out the \SK, with a diamond available too. Hearts are the single-stopper danger: the \HA alone holds the suit, so winning too soon risks West's run. I hold up the heart, then build my spade and club tricks, losing the lead only to the hand that cannot hurt me.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, which looks like top of a sequence, so West likely has the \HQJ and a long suit. I duck and duck again, taking the \HA on the third round to clear East of hearts. Four club tricks, three spades after the \SK is forced out, and the heart make eight, and a diamond brings the ninth; that totals nine. Since East holds the spade and club stoppers, conceding the lead there is safe once West's hearts are dead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
With only one heart stopper, the hold-up was mandatory, and after it East was the safe hand for every later loser. Counting the suit out and ducking the right number of rounds is the whole technique. Nicely managed.}
