declarer-note: DD-necessary hold-up: winning round 1 of the led suit fails. West leads long hearts; duck to exhaust East.
defense: reject
defense-note: declarer-play scenario
}
[Auction "S"]
1N    Pass  3N    Pass
Pass  Pass
{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H6. From \HKQ765 lead fourth-best of your longest, strongest suit; against notrump that attacks before declarer organizes his tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
In 3\N I count two top spades off \SAK, one heart, four clubs off \CAK plus the long clubs, and the diamonds develop to three once the \DK is forced out, which makes nine. The hold-up concern is hearts: the lone \HA is my only guard, so if West regains the lead with hearts running, I am down. I duck hearts to exhaust East, then drive out the \DK, losing that lead to the safe hand.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H6, which looks like a fourth-best, suggesting a five-card suit with honors at the top. I hold up the \HA on the first round so that East, who appears short, runs out of hearts to return. Then I develop diamonds by forcing out the \DK: three diamonds join two spades and four clubs to reach nine. East winning the \DK is harmless, because after the hold-up West can no longer get in to cash hearts.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The key was ducking that first heart so the diamond knockout fell safely on East rather than dangerous West. Identify the single stopper, hold up, then attack the suit that costs the lead only to the safe hand. Excellent timing.}
[BidSystemEW "2/1GF - 2/1 Game Force"]
[BidSystemNS "2/1GF - 2/1 Game Force"]

