{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. With \HKQJ84 you hold a solid sequence, so lead the top of it and drive out declarer's stopper while you still have entries in the suit.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
3\N. Counting sure tricks: two top \S, the \HA, and three top \D give six. The ninth comes from \S, where my \K9853 opposite the \A64 sets up to four tricks once the \Q and \J are knocked out, and a club trick fills the gap. The danger is hearts: with only the lone \HA as a stopper, I must hold up so that when I lose the \S lead, the long heart suit can't run.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, looks like top of a sequence, so West probably holds \HKQJ and a five-card suit. East's heart length is unknown, but if I win the first round and later concede a spade, a defender with four or five hearts cashes out. So I duck the \HK, duck again, and win the third heart with the \A, exhausting East's likely doubleton or tripleton. Now I attack \S, forcing out the \Q and \J; the \S length lands four tricks plus a club, and even if East wins a spade, East has no heart left to return. That makes nine: four \S, three \D, the \HA, and a club.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The hold-up was everything here: ducking two rounds of hearts cut the defenders' communication, so the hand that took the spade trick was the safe one. Establishing spades for the extra tricks brought it home. Nicely judged.}
