{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H8. With \HKQ9875 you have a long, strong six-card suit but the honors don't form a three-card sequence, so lead fourth-best from length.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
3\N. Two top \S, the \HA, two top \D, and a club give six off the top. The development suit is \S, where \AK832 opposite \976 sets up to four tricks, and \D can be stretched to three. Hearts are guarded only by the \HA, so I must hold up to cut the suit before I surrender the lead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H8, looks like a fourth-best, suggesting a six-card suit headed by the \KQ. If I win the first round and later lose a spade, the long hearts would cash. So I duck the first two hearts and take the \HA on the third, exhausting East. Then I run \S to develop four tricks and add a diamond for the ninth; whoever wins a spade has no heart left. Four \S, three \D, the \HA make eight — plus a club to nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Ducking twice was decisive: it left East, not the long-heart hand, on lead. With hearts dead, developing spades and diamonds brought home the contract. Good discipline.}
