{[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. With \HKQJT6 you have a near-solid sequence, so lead the top honor to drive out the stopper and establish your suit.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
3\N. Three top \C, two top \S, and the \HA give six immediately. The ninth trick comes from \D, the development suit, where \KT4 opposite \QJ2 sets up two tricks once the \A is forced out, while clubs can run to five. With the \HA my only heart guard, a hold-up is essential before I give up the lead in diamonds.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \HK, which looks like top of a sequence, so West probably holds \HKQJ and roughly a five-card suit. If I win early and then knock out the \DA, a long-heart defender could cash out. So I duck the first two hearts and win the \HA on the third, stripping East. Then I develop \D, forcing out the \A; diamonds give two tricks while the clubs run for five. East may win the \DA but has no heart to return. Five \C, two \S, the \HA, and a diamond reach nine.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The hold-up cut the defenders' hearts, so conceding the \DA cost nothing. The long club suit plus the developed diamond delivered the count. Well judged.}
